					</header>
					<!-- article content -->
					<article>
						<div class="blog_post">
							Having only purchased the Indie license for Android means I can only develop for the Android platform for now.  I have been taking a course in native android development in Java and have been getting familiar with the structure and naming conventions of native android.  I believe this is important to know as a C# developer new to Xamarin that being familiar with how and android app works is beneficial in learning how to work with an android app in xamarin.
						</div>

						<div class="blog_post">
							My development setup specs:
							<ul>
								<li>Windows 8.1 64 bit</li>
								<li>16 GB RAM</li>
								<li>Intel Core i7-4510U</li>
								<li>Xamarin Studio</li>
								<li>Xamarin Android Player</li>
							</ul>
							I really recommend using the simulator developed by Xamarin, it is my choice for testing apps on my machine.
							<br />You can find the download at the Xamarin website by <a href="https://xamarin.com/android-player"><b>Clicking Here for Xamarin Android Player</b></a>
						</div>
					</article>

					<hr />

				</div>


			</div>

